from 5 to 10 percent of some portfolios for younger  workers in commodity-linked securities. The Afores had  mostly allocated their holdings to the country\u2019s debt markets.\nAfore Banamex, Mexico\u2019s largest pension fund, plans to \u201cgradually\u201d invest as much as 2 percent of total assets in commodities, said Luis Sayeg, the chief executive officer of the bank\u2019s pension unit. The fund will hire a third-party asset manager for such investments, he said in a June 11 interview.\nMexico\u2019s central bank authorized investments for commodities from milk to oil. The Afores will also be able to invest in indexes linked to such securities, the gazette said.\nAfore Banamex manages 289 billion pesos ($22.5 billion), according to data from the country\u2019s pension regulator.\nBarclays Plc (BARC) , BlackRock Inc. (BLK) , Schroders Plc and Deutsche Bank AG (DBK) are among asset managers that were waiting for the final guidelines to enter formal talks with different Afores.\n-- With assistance from Jonathan Levin and Ben Bain in Mexico City. Editors: Dale Crofts, Robin Saponar\nTo contact the reporter on this story: Carlos M. Rodriguez in Mexico City at carlosmr@bloomberg.net .\nTo contact the editor responsible for this story: James Attwood at jattwood3@bloomberg.net\nMore News:\n", "update_time": "2012-10-22 14:25:43", "post_time": "2012-06-15 12:14:24", "author": "Carlos Manuel Rodriguez", "url": "http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-06-15/mexico-121-billion-pension-funds-can-invest-in-commodities-1-.html", "title": "Mexico $121 Billion Pension Funds Can Invest in Commodities", "post_date": "2012-06-15", "source": "Bloomberg News", "stock_index": "COLCAP", "embers_id": "28ee2e05c375d0b25a03ece863e5adb7bd35c282"}, {"content": "JPMorgan to Pay $178 Million for Stake in Sura\u2019s Asset Manager\nBy Christine Jenkins - 2012-06-06T22:16:33Z\nColombia\u2019s Grupo de Inversiones Suramericana SA said JPMorgan Chase & Co. (JPM) agreed to pay $178 million for a st