he said.\n\u201cWe think we are in a slightly different situation than some,\u201d he said.\nThe bank was criticized on May 15 by Pensions & Investment Research Consultants Ltd., a shareholder adviser, for the reliability and audit quality of its accounts, which may be affected by the International Financial Reporting Standards. Shareholders should vote down the audit report, PIRC said.\nUsing the standards is required by regulators, Finance Director Iain Mackay said on today\u2019s conference call. \u201cTo object to a set of international standards is an interesting point of view, but it is simply not a basis on which to recommend that the accounts are not approved.\u201d\nTo contact the reporters on this story: Howard Mustoe in London at hmustoe@bloomberg.net ; Stephanie Tong in Hong Kong at stong17@bloomberg.net\nTo contact the editor responsible for this story: Edward Evans at eevans3@bloomberg.net\nHSBC Expects to Meet Top End of Savings Goal at $3.5B\nChris Ratcliffe/Bloomberg\nHSBC's Canary Wharf offices, right, in London.\nHSBC's Canary Wharf offices, right, in London. Photographer: Chris Ratcliffe/Bloomberg\nMore News:\n", "update_time": "2012-10-22 14:26:05", "post_time": "2012-05-17 04:41:08", "author": "Howard Mustoe , Stephanie Tong", "url": "http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-05-17/hsbc-expects-to-meet-top-end-of-savings-goal-at-3-5-bill.html", "title": "HSBC Doubles Target for Additional Revenue to $2 Billion", "post_date": "2012-05-17", "source": "Bloomberg News", "stock_index": "COLCAP", "embers_id": "cf3a38f4b61e7a46393915ed40bd841d078c4d8c"}, {"content": "Petrominerales Falls on Output Decline, Dry Well: Bogota Mover\nBy Christine Jenkins - 2012-09-12T21:16:08Z\nPetrominerales Ltd. (PMGC) , a Calgary- based oil company that operates in the Andean region, slumped after saying production declined in August and new tests at a Colombian exploration well showed only water.\nShares fell 15 percent to 15,100 pesos at the close of trading in Bogota, the 