ch InBev NV (ABI) were among companies that said they were withdrawing support from Armstrong after the USADA report, according to which the Texan had \u201cengaged in serial cheating.\u201d USADA stripped Armstrong of his seven Tour de France titles in August.\nEarlier today, Stephen Hodge quit as vice-president of Cycling Australia after he admitted doping in a career as a professional rider that ended in 1996.\nTo contact the reporter on this story: Alex Duff in Madrid at aduff4@bloomberg.net\nTo contact the editor responsible for this story: Christopher Elser at celser@bloomberg.net\nMore News:\n", "update_time": "2012-10-22 14:45:23", "post_time": "2012-10-19 10:29:53", "author": "Alex Duff", "url": "http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-10-19/rabobank-drops-pro-cycling-sponsorship-on-u-s-doping-scandal.html", "title": "Rabobank Drops Cycling Sponsorship on U.S. Doping Scandal", "post_date": "2012-10-19", "source": "Bloomberg News", "stock_index": "IBOV", "embers_id": "e779d770a8ebe6510ec4fa2a0ce1f39a01a2019f"}, {"content": "Coca-Cola Retains Title as World\u2019s Most Valuable Brand\nBy Manish Modi - 2012-10-03T03:57:53Z\nFollowing is a table ranking 100 global brands from Interbrand\u2019s Best Global Brands 2012 report .\n================================================================================ -----Rank-----                                             ---Value ($ Bln.)---- 2012 2011 Chng.  Company             Industry                2012     2011  YoY% ================================================================================     1    1    0  Coca-Cola           Beverages            $77.839  $71.861    8%     2    8    6  Apple               Technology           $76.568  $33.492  129%     3    2   -1  IBM                 Business Services    $75.532  $69.905    8%     4    4    0  Google              Technology           $69.726  $55.317   26%     5    3   -2  Microsoft           Technology $57.853  $59.087   -2%     6    5   -1  GE               