sor, with the capacity to handle handle about 100,000 transactions per second, according to a presentation distributed to journalists on Sept. 11. It\u2019s also equipped with filters that track unusual prices and volumes to prevent erroneous trades from entering the system, according to the bourse.\n\u201cIf we had the previous trading platform and we\u2019d received the number of transactions we received today, the system wouldn\u2019t have held up,\u201d Ibarra said. \u201cIn fact, there would have been a recess,\u201d he said, referring to a temporary stoppage of trading.\nTo contact the reporter on this story: Jonathan J. Levin in Mexico City at jlevin20@bloomberg.net\nTo contact the editor responsible for this story: David Papadopoulos at papadopoulos@bloomberg.net\n", "update_time": "2012-10-22 14:38:36", "post_time": "2012-09-14 01:00:00", "author": "Jonathan J. Levin", "url": "http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-09-14/mexican-bourse-plans-to-resolve-data-delays-before-market-opens.html", "title": "Mexican Bourse Plans to Resolve Data Delays Before Market Opens", "post_date": "2012-09-14", "source": "Bloomberg News", "stock_index": "MEXBOL", "embers_id": "591a3c02cd6064295567fb771d61f12206c759a0"}, {"content": "Uncovered Stocks Get Analyst Notice With Mexico Bourse Program\nBy With assistance from Jose Enrique Arrioja - 2012-07-26T05:00:00Z\nChemical distributor Grupo Pochteca SAB (POCHTECB) and paper maker Bio Pappel SAB (PAPPEL*) are among the 20 companies taking part in a Mexican stock exchange pilot program to broaden analyst coverage and boost trading on the bourse.\nThe program creates a panel of industry group representatives, who select equity analysts to research and write about companies without coverage, said Francisco Valle, head of promotion and issuers at the exchange. The analyst reports will be made public through the bourse\u2019s website, he said yesterday in a telephone interview from Mexico City.\nOther companies picking up coverage under the program include real-estate developer Dine SAB (DINEB) , broadcaster Grupo Radio Centro SAB and pharmacy operator Farmacias Benavides SAB, according to Valle. Analysts received their first assignments yesterday and the first reports will be published within 90 days, he said.\n\u201cWe\u2019re going to help create a parallel professional analysis industry in Mexico ,\u201d Valle said. \u201cWe\u2019re also going to have better pricing and therefore greater trading.\u201d\nSimilar programs have produced successful results in markets including Australia and Malaysia , he said.\nThe research groups participating as analysts include Prognosis Economia Finanzas e Inversiones SC, 414 Capital Inc. Bursametrica SA and the local unit of Morningstar Inc. (MORN)\nCompanies that participate in the program will pay $18,250 annually, Valle said. The exchange will partially subsidize the fee for those that have a float of at least 30 percent, have at least 300 investors, maintain a website and have an investor relations department, he said.\n\u201cThe idea is to make these companies known to the broad investor public,\u201d Gerardo Copca , an analyst with Metanalisis SA, said in a telephone interview from Mexico City.\n", "update_time": "2012-10-22 14:38:38", "post_time": "2012-07-26 01:00:00", "author": "With assistance from Jose Enrique Arrioja", "url": "http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-07-26/uncovered-stocks-get-analyst-notice-with-mexico-bourse-program.html", "title": "Uncovered Stocks Get Analyst Notice With Mexico Bourse Program", "post_date": "2012-07-26", "source": "Bloomberg News", "stock_index": "MEXBOL", "embers_id": "1f6f36831af617b46ed16f078d260ea50b91a2e6"}, {"content": "Mexico Stocks: Sare Holding, Elektra, Bolsa Mexicana Were Active\nBy Jonathan J. Levin - 2012-07-04T20:43:15Z\nThe following companies had unusual price changes in Mexico City trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses, and prices are as of the close of trading.\nThe IPC index fell 0.2 percent to