* MM) soared a record 7.4 percent to 21.22 pesos. The local unit of Spanish construction company Obrascon Huarte Lain SA joined the benchmark IPC index at the start of this month.\nTo contact the reporter on this story: Katia Porzecanski in New York at kporzecansk1@bloomberg.net\nTo contact the editor responsible for this story: David Papadopoulos at papadopoulos@bloomberg.net\nMore News:\n", "update_time": "2012-10-22 14:44:25", "post_time": "2011-09-27 18:07:49", "author": "Katia Porzecanski", "url": "http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-27/mexican-stocks-grupo-mexico-industrias-penoles-mexichem-gain.html", "title": "Mexican Stocks: Grupo Mexico, Mexichem, OHL Mexico Advance", "post_date": "2011-09-27", "source": "Bloomberg News", "stock_index": "MEXBOL", "embers_id": "bb124aa0aabd846701ee99f890042a17795dba6c"}, {"content": "Mexico Stocks: Cemex, Organizacion Soriana Gain; Minera Drops\nBy Jonathan J. Levin - 2011-09-15T20:36:22Z\nThe following companies had unusual price changes in Mexico trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are as of 4 p.m. New York time.\nThe IPC index rose 1.5 percent to 35,181.44.\nMost Mexican stocks followed U.S. equities higher as the European Central Bank said it will lend dollars to euro-area banks in a series of three-month loans to ensure they have enough of the U.S. currency through the end of the year.\nCemex SAB (CEMEXCPO MM), the largest cement maker in the Americas, gained 2.2 percent to 6.62 pesos. Organizacion Soriana SAB (SORIANAB MM), Mexico\u2019s second-largest grocery store chain, gained 5.1 percent to 29.03 pesos.\nMinera Frisco SAB (MFRISCOA MM), the mining company controlled by billionaire Carlos Slim , fell 1.9 percent to 47.16 pesos. Silver for December delivery in New York slipped as much as 2.8 percent to $40.84 an ounce.\nTo contact the reporter on this story: Jonathan J. Levin in Mexico City at jlevin20@bloomberg.net\nTo contact the editor responsible for this story: David Papadopoulos at papadopou