arti Enterprises.\nInternational retailers including Carrefour SA (CA) and Tesco Plc (TSCO) have been setting up wholesale operations to gain a foothold in India, where policy makers had debated the ownership rules for retail for at least seven years. The change in rules allows overseas supermarket chains to own as much as 51 percent in local ventures.\nIndia Venture\nIn 2007, Wal-Mart formed a joint venture in India for wholesale stores and has been building a supply chain and logistics network in the country.\nWal-Mart owns a 50 percent stake in the wholesale-venture with Bharti. Closely held Bharti runs its own chain of more than 186 Easyday stores including supermarkets. Bharti Airtel Ltd. (BHARTI) , India\u2019s largest mobile phone carrier, is a part of the Bharti group.\nWal-Mart can meet the minimum $100 million investment set by the government and the requirement for overseas companies to spend at least 50 percent of that on back-end infrastructure within three years, Price said.\nWal-Mart fell 0.6 percent to $76.56 yesterday in New York.\nTo contact the reporters on this story: Unni Krishnan in New Delhi at ukrishnan2@bloomberg.net ; Malavika Sharma in New Delhi at msharma52@bloomberg.net\nTo contact the editors responsible for this story: Robin Ajello at rajello@bloomberg.net ; Stephanie Wong at swong139@bloomberg.net\n", "update_time": "2012-10-22 14:44:58", "post_time": "2012-10-19 08:48:19", "author": "Unni Krishnan , Malavika Sharma", "url": "http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-10-19/india-government-gets-query-on-wal-mart-investments-official.html", "title": "India Is Said to Get Query on Wal-Mart Investments", "post_date": "2012-10-19", "source": "Bloomberg News", "stock_index": "MEXBOL", "embers_id": "0eb2aa652f75352d7e32f6480836efde1d0ea297"}]}